task_1.query_used: Search LinkedIn for Ali Khaledi Nasab profiles with AI researcher or artificial intelligence specialization
task_1.data: Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist and AI scientist currently working at Amazon Rufus. Originally from Iran, he moved to the United States in 2014 to pursue his Ph.D. After completing his doctorate, he joined Stanford University's Department of Neurosurgery, focusing on developing stimulation methods for treating neurological disorders, including Parkinson's disease. In 2021, he transitioned to CODA Biotherapeutics, a gene therapy startup targeting epilepsy treatments. Following the closure of CODA in 2022 due to funding challenges, he joined Amazon as a research scientist in the AWS network capacity team. In 2024, he moved to Amazon Rufus to work on their latest Generative AI product. Throughout his career, Dr. Khaledi Nasab has contributed to various research projects, including studies on coordinated reset stimulation for neurological disorders and the dynamics of phase oscillator networks with synaptic weight and structural plasticity. He is also the editor for the Brain Development section of the "Encyclopedia of Child and Adolescent Health," which received the 2024 PROSE Award for "significant contributions" in Clinical Medicine. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

task_3.query_used: Search IEEE Xplore and ACM Digital Library for research papers authored by Ali Khaledi Nasab
task_3.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab has contributed to various research areas, including physics, neuroscience, and social sciences. Below is a summary of his notable works:

**1. "Standing up to fear"**

In this article, Khaledi Nasab reflects on the challenges faced by international students in the U.S. following the 2017 travel ban. He discusses the climate of fear and uncertainty, emphasizing the need for institutional support for immigrant scientists. The piece was published in *Science* magazine in April 2017. ([academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/32689067/Standing_up_to_fear?utm_source=openai))

**2. "Information processing in tree networks of excitable elements"**

Co-authored with J. Kromer and L. Schimansky-Geier, this study examines the collective response of small random tree networks of diffusively coupled excitable elements. The research, published in *Physical Review E* in 2021, provides insights into the dynamics of these networks. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

**3. "Long-Lasting Desynchronization Effects of Coordinated Reset Stimulation Improved by Random Jitters"**

In this paper, Khaledi Nasab and his colleagues investigate the impact of coordinated reset stimulation on neural networks, focusing on the effects of introducing random jitters. The study, published in *Frontiers in Physiology* in 2021, offers valuable insights into neural desynchronization mechanisms. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

**4. "Variability of collective dynamics in random tree networks of strongly coupled stochastic excitable elements"**

This research delves into the collective dynamics of strongly diffusively coupled excitable elements on small random tree networks. Published in *Physical Review E* in 2018, the study provides a comprehensive analysis of these complex systems. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

**5. "Kerr nonlinearity due to intersubband transitions in a three-level InAs/GaAs quantum dot: the impact of a wetting layer on dispersion curves"**

Co-authored with M. Sabaeian, M. Sahrai, and V. Fallahi, this paper investigates the Kerr nonlinearity in a three-level InAs/GaAs quantum dot system, emphasizing the role of the wetting layer on dispersion curves. The study was published in *Journal of Optics* in 2014. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

These publications highlight Khaledi Nasab's interdisciplinary research contributions across physics, neuroscience, and social sciences.

task_5.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist and researcher with a diverse academic and professional background. He earned his Ph.D. in Physics and Astronomy from Ohio University, where he focused on the dynamics of excitable tree networks in sensory neurons. His doctoral research was supervised by Dr. Alexander Neiman. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2017/10/khaledi-nasab-gives-colloquium-talk-college-wooster/?utm_source=openai))

After completing his Ph.D., Khaledi Nasab joined Stanford University as a postdoctoral researcher in the Department of Neurosurgery, collaborating with Dr. Peter Tass. During this period, he worked on developing stimulation methods for treating neurological disorders, including Parkinson's disease. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/about?utm_source=openai))

In 2021, he became a Senior Researcher at Amazon Web Services (AWS) in Seattle, focusing on network capacity planning. Additionally, he initiated a personal research project called "Night Science," exploring interdisciplinary problems at the intersection of nonlinear dynamics, computer science, and artificial intelligence. One of his publications from this project is titled "Depolarization of echo chambers by random dynamical nudge," published in Scientific Reports in 2022. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/about?utm_source=openai))

Regarding his involvement with specific companies, there is no publicly available information indicating that Khaledi Nasab has founded or holds affiliations with any particular companies. His professional activities appear to be primarily within academic and research institutions.

task_3.query_used: Search IEEE Xplore and ACM Digital Library for research papers authored by Ali Khaledi Nasab
task_3.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab has contributed to various research areas, including physics, neuroscience, and social sciences. Below is a summary of his notable works:

**1. "Standing up to fear"**

In this article, Khaledi Nasab reflects on the challenges faced by international students in the U.S. following the 2017 travel ban. He discusses the climate of fear and uncertainty, emphasizing the need for institutional support for immigrant scientists. The piece was published in *Science* magazine in April 2017. ([academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/32689067/Standing_up_to_fear?utm_source=openai))

**2. "Information processing in tree networks of excitable elements"**

Co-authored with J. Kromer and L. Schimansky-Geier, this study examines the collective response of small random tree networks of diffusively coupled excitable elements. The research, published in *Physical Review E* in 2021, provides insights into the dynamics of these networks. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

**3. "Long-Lasting Desynchronization Effects of Coordinated Reset Stimulation Improved by Random Jitters"**

In this paper, Khaledi Nasab and his colleagues investigate the impact of coordinated reset stimulation on neural networks, focusing on the effects of introducing random jitters. The study, published in *Frontiers in Physiology* in 2021, offers valuable insights into neural desynchronization mechanisms. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

**4. "Variability of collective dynamics in random tree networks of strongly coupled stochastic excitable elements"**

This research delves into the collective dynamics of strongly diffusively coupled excitable elements on small random tree networks. Published in *Physical Review E* in 2018, the study provides a comprehensive analysis of these complex systems. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

**5. "Kerr nonlinearity due to intersubband transitions in a three-level InAs/GaAs quantum dot: the impact of a wetting layer on dispersion curves"**

Co-authored with M. Sabaeian, M. Sahrai, and V. Fallahi, this paper investigates the Kerr nonlinearity in a three-level InAs/GaAs quantum dot system, emphasizing the role of the wetting layer on dispersion curves. The study was published in *Journal of Optics* in 2014. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

These publications highlight Khaledi Nasab's interdisciplinary research contributions across physics, neuroscience, and social sciences.

task_5.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist and researcher with a diverse academic and professional background. He earned his Ph.D. in Physics and Astronomy from Ohio University, where he focused on the dynamics of excitable tree networks in sensory neurons. His doctoral research was supervised by Dr. Alexander Neiman. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2017/10/khaledi-nasab-gives-colloquium-talk-college-wooster/?utm_source=openai))

After completing his Ph.D., Khaledi Nasab joined Stanford University as a postdoctoral researcher in the Department of Neurosurgery, collaborating with Dr. Peter Tass. During this period, he worked on developing stimulation methods for treating neurological disorders, including Parkinson's disease. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/about?utm_source=openai))

In 2021, he became a Senior Researcher at Amazon Web Services (AWS) in Seattle, focusing on network capacity planning. Additionally, he initiated a personal research project called "Night Science," exploring interdisciplinary problems at the intersection of nonlinear dynamics, computer science, and artificial intelligence. One of his publications from this project is titled "Depolarization of echo chambers by random dynamical nudge," published in Scientific Reports in 2022. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/about?utm_source=openai))

Regarding his involvement with specific companies, there is no publicly available information indicating that Khaledi Nasab has founded or holds affiliations with any particular companies. His professional activities appear to be primarily within academic and research institutions.
